'<p>The Latin <em>Elucidarium</em>(or <em>Elucidarius, Lucidarius</em>) is a handbook of religious instruction in the form of a pacey dialogue between a student and teacher, in which common questions about the Christian Faith are matched with simple and undemanding answers. The <em>Elucidarium</em>was composed in Latin near the turn of the twelfth century, its authorship is uncertainly attributed to Honorius Augustodunensis (b. 1075-80, d. 1156), a theologian and populariser of religious learning figure about whom we know little.<a title="" name="_ftnref1" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn1">[1]</a>For students, its three books provided a rudimentary <em>summa</em>of Christian teachings on the nature of God, salvation through the church, and Christian eschatology, while for teachers it provided a store of concise and uncomplicated answers to common questions. ‘How can one God be a trinity?’ ‘Where does God live?’ ‘If God is called glory and kindness, why do we call him ‘father’ and not ‘mother”? ‘Why do some wicked men live long and some good men die young?’<a title="" name="_ftnref2" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn2">[2]</a>Its perspective on these challenging theological questions is seldom subtle or convoluted, but has been characterised, variously, as concise and undemanding, crude and naive.<a title="" name="_ftnref3" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn3">[3]</a></p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The composition of the <em>Elucidarium</em>was timely with a new vogue for encyclopaedias, single-volume anthologies of statements from authoritative authors on diverse religious and natural philosophical subjects. The formal structure provided by the dialogue format rendered itopen to tailoring and alteration, and some of the questions added may have strayed from religious themes. For example, in the Castilian translation of the<em>Elucidarium</em>, composed in around 1293, the student asks ‘Why does it damage trees to strip off their bark but not the cork tree?’<a title="" name="_ftnref4" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn4">[4]</a></p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The <em>Elucidarium </em>was evidently a work of enduring popularityacross high and late medieval Europe, surviving in hundreds of manuscripts. One of the ways the <em>Elucidarius</em>was made undemanding to its audiences was thorough its translation into local languages.<a title="" name="_ftnref5" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn5">[5]</a>In a four-hundred year period, itwas translated into languages including Old Norse-Icelandic, Continental and Insular French, Old and Middle English, Middle Welsh, Middle High German, Provençal, Occitan, Castillian, and Czech.</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The present survey is based on the following translations:</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>-      <em>Elucidarius</em>(Old Norse-Icelandic), two independent translations (earliest <em>c. </em> 1200?).</p>'+
'<p>-      <em>Elucidarium</em>(Old English), two excerpts in the same manuscript but by separate hands, but likely the work of the same translator (manuscript s. XII mid)</p>'+
'<p>-      <em>Lucidarie</em>(Middle English),A Middle English translation with numerous interpolations (s. XIV in)</p>'+
'<p>-      <em>Lucistrye</em>(Middle English), A Middle English translation related to the <em>Lucidarie</em>, but less careful and complete (s. XV in)</p>'+
'<p>-      <em>Abbreviated Middle English Elucidarium</em>(Middle English), an English translation of the  <em>Elucidarium</em>from a Latin original (s XV ex)</p>'+
'<p>-       <em>Ystoria Lucidar</em>(Middle Welsh), (s. XIII ex / XIV in)</p>'+
'<p>-      <em>The Lucydarye </em>(Middle English), a late Middle English translation of the French <em>Second Lucidaire </em>extant in two print versions, published 1502-4 and ?1523.</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>Its Insular transmission cannot be understood in isolation from its wider Continental transmission. As manuscript examples assembled by Huw Grange show, the <em>Elucidarium</em>circulated within England in both Continental and Insular varieties of French. For example, Oxford Bodleian Library Bodley 652 (s. XIII 2) and Oxford, Bodleian Library, Douce270 (s.XIII mid, for Wells Cathedral in Somerset?) both contain the Old French <em>Lucidaire I</em>among other items in Latin, Middle English and Insular French.<a title="" name="_ftnref6" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn6">[6]</a>When the <em>Elucidarium</em>appeared in print in a Middle English translation, <em>The Lucydarye </em>(1502-04, ?1523), the translator did not base his translation on the original Latin text – or one of the pre-existing English translations - but on an earlier French translation.</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>There is a tendency in Insular manuscripts for compilers to bring together various versions of this enormously popular work.A vernacular translation of a work did not necessarily displace the Latin original, but may have circulated with it. For example, Latin and Insular French versions of the Elucidarium are preserved side-by-side in London, Lambeth Palace Library, 431 (s. XIII in),the Latin text (ff. 183r–210v) immediately preceding the<em>Lucidaire III</em>(ff. 210v–238v).<a title="" name="_ftnref7" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn7">[7]</a>Having acquired a fragmentary version of a popular work, a compositor may have sought a more complete version, or, in multilingual insular environments, a complementary translation into another language. Two Old Norse versions of the <em>Elucidarium</em>– one fragmentary, and one fuller witness – likely circulated together in the single-volume library substitute known as Hauksbók (now Copenhagen, Arnamagnæan Institute, AM 544 4to and AM 675 4to), compiled for the Icelandic statesman Haukr Erlendsson (d. 1334). One English and two Welsh translations of the <em>Elucidarium</em>circulated together in National Library of Wales, MS Peniarth 12, a composite manuscript containing texts written by four hands between <em>c. </em>1400 and the 1580s. The compilation includes a fragmentary Welsh translation, the <em>Ystoria Lucidar</em>, written <em>c. </em>1400, which the book’s sixteenth-century owner, Hugh Evans, also supplemented with readings from another Welsh translation to create a ‘complete’ text. This hybrid Welsh text was additionally bound with an abbreviated Middle English <em>Elucidarium</em>, written <em>c. </em>1475-1500.</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The manuscript compilations containing versions of the <em>Elucidarium</em>intwo languages – Latin and French, English and Welsh – reveal much about the Insular mobility of popular works, and the multilingual environments through which they moved. An inclusive view of the movements of these texts across national and linguistic borders enables a deeper understanding of the literary cultures that produced them.</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">English Transmission</span></strong></p>'+
'<p>The <em>Elucidarium</em>was translated into Old English within a few years of its completion, appearing alongside homiletic, hagiographic and instructive material in London, British Library, Cotton Vespasian D. xiv, ff. 159r-163v and 163v-165r  (s. XII med, ?Christ Church, Canterbury, England).<a title="" name="_ftnref8" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn8">[8]</a>The translation comprises two excerpts of selected dialogical units from the second and the first book of the <em>Elucidarium</em>(in that order). The questions chosen from the second book (a condensed translation of chapters 1-6) concerns the nature of Sin, and the earthly fortunes of the good and the sinful; while the later selection from the first book (a condensed translation of chapters 23-25) concerns the resurrection and ascension. The two pieces, probably the original work of the same translator but written here in two different hands, are separated by red and green decoration. The manuscript comprises items written mostly in the vernacular Old English.<a title="" name="_ftnref9" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn9">[9]</a>        </p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The <em>Elucidarium</em>underwent at least two translations from Latin into Middle English.<a title="" name="_ftnref10" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn10">[10]</a>One translation, known as<em>Lucistrye</em>, is preserved a compendium of religious items written primarily in English with some Latin in St John\'s College, Cambridge, MS G.25, fols. 1r-16r, s. XV in.<a title="" name="_ftnref11" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn11">[11]</a>The translation follows closely the structure of the Latin <em>Elucidarium</em>as far as the beginning of its second book, but then contains only six questions from the second book, and omits the third altogether. This translation is related to the version in Cambridge University Library MS Ii.vi.26, fols. 79v-101v (s. XV in) called <em>Lucidaire</em>.This manuscript contains a number of tracts advocating the Bible’s translation into English.<a title="" name="_ftnref12" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn12">[12]</a>This translation is related to, but is generally less conscientious and complete than, the translation in St John’s College, Cambridge, MS G.25, and it is likely that the two originated in a common exemplar.                                                                                                                      </p>'+
'<p>The <em>Abbreviated Middle English Elucidarium</em>has been considerably adapted and refocussed from its Latin original, and is preserved in National Library of Wales, MS Peniarth 12 (previously Hengwrt 202), ff. 1r-11v (s. XV 3/4). The section containing the English <em>Elucidarium </em>was written by an unknown scribe from Worcestershire or (more likely) South Herefordshire, which suits its later inclusion in a manuscript containing Welsh language texts.<a title="" name="_ftnref13" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn13">[13]</a>The translation seems to have been translated from Latin recently to its copying in this manuscript.<a title="" name="_ftnref14" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn14">[14]</a>Of the 368 chapters in the Lefèvre’s Latin edition, 120 have Middle English counterparts in this version. The text seems never to have been finished, ending in the middle of a sentence with space remaining on the folio.<a title="" name="_ftnref15" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn15">[15]</a>This Middle English translation is bound into a complex composite manuscript that bears the inscription ‘llyfr Hugh Evans yw hwn Anno 1583’ (‘This is Hugh Evans\'s Book, 1583’).<a title="" name="_ftnref16" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn16">[16]</a>The manuscript contains texts written by four hands, between <em>c.</em>1400 and<em>c. </em>1580. On the blank leaves that follow it, the manuscript’s compilator (Hugh Evans?) has copied numerous Welsh language religious writings, beginning with a Welsh translation of the <em>Elucidarium</em>, the <em>Ystoria Lucidar</em>(a translation from Latin, not the preceding English version) on folios 12-38, 39-58, and 67-73. At the end of the Middle English <em>Elucidarium</em>, Hugh Evans has written a marginal note reading ‘finis angli’ (‘the English [version] finishes’).<a title="" name="_ftnref17" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn17">[17]</a>The inclusion of a Middle English <em>Elucidarium</em>(c. 1475-1500) seems to have stimulated by the compositor’s possession of a Welsh translation, the <em>Ystoria Lucidar</em>(<em>c.</em>1400, and supplemented <em>c. </em>1580).</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The <em>Elucidarium</em>’s transmission in English translation was not halted by the advent of print technologies. The <em>Lucydarye</em>was printed by the London-based publisher Wynkyn de Worde (d. 1534) in 1502-04 and ?1523.<a title="" name="_ftnref18" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn18">[18]</a>The translator, Andrew Chertsey (fl. 1502-27), did not base his translation on the original Latin text – or one of the pre-existing English translations - but on the French <em>Second Lucidaire</em>.The younger version was set up directly from a copy of the elder.<a title="" name="_ftnref19" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn19">[19]</a>The elder version(1502-04) survives in only one copy (ESTC 13685.5, Folger Shakespeare Library, Washington DC).<a title="" name="_ftnref20" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn20">[20]</a>The younger version (1523?), containing 12 woodcut illustrations from four designs, also survives in only one copy (ESTC 13686, British Library Print (Br)).<a title="" name="_ftnref21" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn21">[21]</a></p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Icelandic Transmission</span></strong></p>'+
'<p>The Old Norse <em>Elucidarius</em>survives in eight manuscript witnesses, none of which preserve a complete text.<a title="" name="_ftnref22" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn22">[22]</a>Three manuscripts cover what exists of the translation – AM 674a 4to, AM 675 4to, and AM 238 fol. XVIII (all in Copenhagen’s Arnamagnæan Institute) – with a single passage drawn from AM 544 4to. The full translation extends, in Firchow’s estimation, to around 80 percent of the length of the Latin.<a title="" name="_ftnref23" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn23">[23]</a></p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The fullest witness spans thirty-three folios in AM 674a 4to (s. XII 2), which has the distinction of being one of the oldest surviving Icelandic manuscripts.<a title="" name="_ftnref24" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn24">[24]</a>The second major witness spans sixteen folios in AM 675 4to (1290-1310). This manuscript seems to have been copied by an Icelandic scribe living in Norway, possibly for inclusion in Hauksbók, an idiosyncratic compilation of sagas, historical writings, and items on natural philosophy commissioned, and partly written, by the Icelandic statesman Haukr Erlendsson (d. 1334).<a title="" name="_ftnref25" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn25">[25]</a>  </p>'+
'<p>If this text was written for inclusion in Hauksbók, it would be the second text of the <em>Elucidarium </em>in Haukr’s possession. A fragmentary Old Norse translation, running to only two passages, is preserved inthe second (and largest) section of Hauksbók that now exists as Copenhagen, Arnamagnæan Institute, AM 544 4to, ff. 10v-11v (s. XIV in).<a title="" name="_ftnref26" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn26">[26]</a>This section contains a diverse and idiosyncratic selection of texts including a version of the Eddic poem <em>Völuspá</em>, (ff. 22r-33v), the Icelandic <em>Breta sögur </em>(an Old Norse adaptation of Geoffrey of Monmouth’s <em>History of the Kings of Britain</em>) including <em>Merlínusspá</em>(a verse translation of <em>Merlin’s Prophecy</em>) (ff. 60r-68v). This fragmentary translation of the <em>Elucidarium </em>was copied by a (Norwegian?) scribe for Haukr, who then seems to have acquired a more complete version in AM 675 4to. The preeminent seventeenth-century collector of Icelandic manuscripts, Árni Magnússon, says that Hauksbók included <em>Elucidarius</em>, but the manuscript was taken apart after his death. It is thought, but not known, that AM 675 4to is the Hauksbók <em>Elucidarius</em>.<a title="" name="_ftnref27" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn27">[27]</a></p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>There are besides a number of more minor witnesses. Copenhagen, Arnamagnæan Institute, AM 229 fol. IV (s. XIV 2) contains short passages from the <em>Elucidarius</em>(f. 2v) alongside excerpts from <em>Gyðinga saga</em>(<em>Saga of the Jewish People</em>)(ff. 1r-2r).<a title="" name="_ftnref28" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn28">[28]</a>Passages from the <em>Elucidarius</em>are preserved with religious and philosophical treatises in Copenhagen, Arnamagnæan Institute, AM 685d 4to, ff. 8v-10v (s. XV 2),<a title="" name="_ftnref29" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn29">[29]</a>and Copenhagen, Arnamagnæan Institute, AM 685b 4to (s. XV 2).<a title="" name="_ftnref30" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn30">[30]</a>Copenhagen, Arnamagnæan Institute, AM 238 fol. XVIII (s. XV 2- s. XVI 1) comprises four leaves, three containing the <em>Elucidarius</em>, with a portion of a sermon on the fourth.<a title="" name="_ftnref31" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn31">[31]</a>An eight-line fragment n Reykjavík, Stofnun Árna Magnússonar, AM 238 fol. XIX (c. 1400) may represent an independent translation of the <em>Elucidarius</em>, inserted into a text of <em>Biblíu saga</em>(<em>Saga of the Bible</em>).<a title="" name="_ftnref32" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn32">[32]</a>                                    </p>'+
'<p><strong>                                    </strong></p>'+
'<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Welsh Translation</span></strong></p>'+
'<p>The <em>Elucidarium</em>existed in at least three Welsh translations,which usually circulated in anthologies of religious texts.<a title="" name="_ftnref33" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn33">[33]</a>The earliest of these is a fragmentary witness in Aberystwyth, National Library of Wales MS. Peniarth 21, ff. 40r-41v (olim Hengwrt 50;s. XIII/XIV).<a title="" name="_ftnref34" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn34">[34]</a>The most copied translation, the<em>,</em><em>Ystoria Lucidar</em>,is extant in five manuscripts, and follows closely the Latin text as it is presented in Lefèvre’s 1954 edition.<a title="" name="_ftnref35" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn35">[35]</a>This translation has been published, taking its base text as Aberystwyth, National Library of Wales MS. Llanstephan 27, ff. 1r-26r (olim <em>The Red Book of Talgarth, </em>s. XIV/XV) and drawing variants from other manuscripts.<a title="" name="_ftnref36" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn36">[36]</a>Llanstephan 27 is the most heterogeneous manuscript containing the <em>Ystoria Lucidar</em>, including both religious texts, charms and prayers in Latin, and a diverse selection of ʻproverbial material, pseudo-scientific material dealing with the interpretation of dreams and signs, and some poetryʼ.<a title="" name="_ftnref37" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn37">[37]</a>It was written by Hywel Fychan, known for his work on the famous Red Book of Hergest (Llyfr Coch Hergest; Oxford, Jesus College MS 111).</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>At some point in the transmission of this manuscript, three quires became separated and now belong to other manuscripts. Two quires containing a text of the <em>Ystoria Luicidar </em>became part of <em> </em>Aberystwyth, National Library of Wales, MS Peniarth 12 (olim Hengwrt 202), ff. 39r-58v.<a title="" name="_ftnref38" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn38">[38]</a>This manuscript is a compilation of texts written by four hands, between around 1400 to around 1580 that bears the inscription \'This is Hugh Evans\'s Book, 1583\' (\'llyfr Hugh Evans yw hwn Anno 1583\'). Around the earlier part, which are two quires from Llanstephan 27, the text was added (ff. 12r-38v and 67r-73r) by the book\'s owner, Hugh Evans, c. 1580, who supplemented this older fragment with a text drawn from another Welsh translation of the Elucidarium to create a ‘complete’ text. On the blank leaves that follow the Middle English <em>Elucidarium</em>(c. 1475-1500) in the same book, the compilator (Hugh Evans?) has copied numerous religious instructional materials written in Welsh, English, and Latin.</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>A complete version of the text is found in Oxford, Jesus College MS. 119 (The Book of the Anchorite of Llanddewi Brefi, earlier Jesus College MS. 2), ff. 5r-69v (1346),<a title="" name="_ftnref39" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn39">[39]</a>a collection of religious prose written for the noble layman Gruffudd ap Llywelyn ap Phylip ap Trahaearn of Cantref Mawr, whose family had long been associated with their patronage of native poetry and the production of manuscripts containing translations of texts from Latin or French.<a title="" name="_ftnref40" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn40">[40]</a>Aberystwyth, National Library of Wales MS. Peniarth 15, p. 62-115 (s. XIV/XV),<a title="" name="_ftnref41" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn41">[41]</a>another anthology of religious prose, has a text of <em>Ystoria Lucidar</em>which was either copied from Oxford, Jesus College MS. 119 or stems from a common source.      </p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>Another witness to this translation is found in Aberystwyth, National Library of Wales MS. Peniarth 190 (s. XIV/XV, Wales).<a title="" name="_ftnref42" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn42">[42]</a>The scribe of this manuscript is designated by Daniel Huws \'X91\', and is elsewhere responsible for a part of the Red Book of Hergest (Oxford Jesus College 111), as well as Llyfr Teg (Peniarth 32), Peniarth 19, and Llanstephan 4.<a title="" name="_ftnref43" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn43">[43]</a>A similar version of this text is in Oxford, Jesus College MS. 23 (earlier 5), pp.1-110 (s. XV 1, Wales),  missing some leaves from its beginning.<a title="" name="_ftnref44" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftn44">[44]</a></p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Conclusion</span></strong></p>'+
'<p>The Insular transmission of the <em>Elucidarium</em>began within just a few years of its completion <em>c. </em>1200, and continues into the early days of print. Its aim to elucidate the Faith and to render its teachings understandable compelled its translation into local languages, making it accessible to members of the lower clergy whose ability in Latin may have prevented them from accessing more advanced Latin <em>summæ</em>. Its vernacular translations also furnished preachers and teachers with a repertoire of responses to common questions in the local language. </p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p>The Insular transmission of the <em>Elucidarium</em>and its vernacular issue challenges the writing of literary histories along national lines, showing how popular works cross national and linguistic borders. Manuscripts of English production contain versions of the <em>Elucidarium</em>written in Latin, Continental and Insular varieties of French, Welsh and English. In beginning to map the vernacular translations of a particularly mobile work like the <em>Elucidarium</em>, we are able to see that borders within – and, indeed, beyond – the Insular world were permeable. Manuscript books sometimes enacted the openness of these borders by including versions of the same work in multiple versions or languages.</p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p> </p>'+
'<p><strong>EDITIONS</strong></p>'+
