'<p><a title="" name="_ftn3" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftnref3">[3]</a>On the <em>Elucidarium</em>and other dialogues between students and their teachers, see Claire M. Waters, <em>Translating Clergie: Status, Education, and Salvation in Thirteenth-Century Vernacular Texts</em>(Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 2016), p. 28. On its conception and eleventh-century monasticism, see Valerie I. J. Flint, ‘The <em>Elucidarius</em>of Honorius Augustodunensis and Reform in Late Eleventh-Century England’, <em>Revue Bénédictine</em>85 (1975): 178–89. The view of Honorius as simplifier is also presented in Aron Gurevich, <em>Medieval Popular Culture: Problems of Belief and Perception</em>(Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1988), pp. 153-75. Others, however, have pointed towards thecomplexity of Honorius’s understanding of predestination and free will. See Walter Hannam, ‘The<em>Ineuitabile </em>of Honorius Augustodunensis: A Study in the Textures of early Twelfth-Century Augustinianisms’ (Unpublished PhD thesis, Boston College, 2013). </p>'+
