'<p><a title="" name="_ftn16" href="applewebdata://91A5BC74-F8A7-4A8C-86F6-8C3BCBAFC6D2#_ftnref16">[16]</a>The alumni records of Oxford University indicate that Brasenose College produced a Masters graduate by that name in 1553. This Hugh went on to become dean of St Asaph in 1560, and, around the time Peniarth 12 was compiled, was either rector at Cerrig-y-Druidion (1582-87) or vicar at Henllan in Denbighshire (1582). These Hughs may - though it cannot be proven - have been one and the same. O\'Rourke, ‘English and Latin’, p. 55.</p>'+
